NL Opt 2: Operations Analysis and DataFrames¶

Packages Used: Functions from the following packages are used below (* indicates first time used).

  • DataFrames*
  • Optim
  • Plots
  • Random
  • Statistics
  • XLSX*

1. Operations Analysis¶

Ex 1: One-Time Vaccine Fulfillment Operations¶

A new vaccine fulfillment center has been established that has the capacity to serve 13 customers. The dispensing and sterile packaging equipment can only fill one common-size container per customer because the set-up time to change the container size is very time-consuming. Since each customer has a different demand, it is not clear what size container should be used. The revenue received per unit of demand is \$5 and the cost to provide each unit is \\$1. Once opened, each container must be used over a short period of time, and, since the customers are dispersed geographically, it is not possible for them to share the vaccine. Determine the common size for the containers that will maximize profit given demands of 237, 214, 161, 146, 331, 159, 423, 332, 139, 327, 152, 98, and 116 units per customer.

Step 1: Display the data¶

It is a good idea to look at the data to see if there is a pattern to the data and check to see if there are any anomalous, outlier data that could be erroneous. If anything is found, it might be possible to ask whoever provided the data about the issue before doing any further analysis. If some data is in error, then it can be deleted; outlier data sould not automatically be eliminated unless it is a real error.

It is easy to display 1-D, a little harder but doable for 2-D, and difficult for 3+ degree data, where the best you can do usually is look at different 1- and 2-D cross-sections of the day. For this data, since there is no time element, a histogram is used instead of a scatter or line plot.

In [1]:
using Plots
d = [237, 214, 161, 146, 331, 159, 423, 332, 139, 327, 152, 98, 116]
histogram(d, legend=false, xlabel="Demand", ylabel="Count")
Out[1]:

Step 2: Determine total profit as a function of container size¶

$ \quad \begin{eqnarray} \mbox{Profit: } \pi(q) &=& \begin{cases} pd - cq, & \mbox{if } q > d \\ pq - cq = (p - c)\,q, & \mbox{otherwise } \end{cases} \\ &=& p \min \bigl\{ q,d \bigr\} - cq \end{eqnarray}$

In [2]:
p = 5                                    # Unit price
c = 1                                    # Unit cost
fπ(q,di) = p*minimum([q, di]) - c*q      # Profit (fπ ⟹ f\pi<TAB>)  
fΠ(q,d) = sum([fπ(q,di) for di in d])    # Total profit (fΠ ⟹ f\Pi<TAB>)
plot([fΠ(qi,d) for qi = 0:500], legend=false, xlabel="Demand", ylabel="Total Profit")
Out[2]:

Step 3: Determine container size that maximizes total profit¶

In [3]:
using Optim
qᵒ = optimize(q -> -fΠ(q,d), 0, 500).minimizer    # (qᵒ ⟹ q\^o<TAB>)
display(scatter!([qᵒ],[fΠ(qᵒ,d)]))
qᵒ, fΠ(qᵒ,d)
Out[3]:
(330.9999976747946, 9406.999995349586)

Ex 2: Periodic Vaccine Fulfillment Operations¶

This example uses the same data as Ex 1, except that, instead of the demand coming at one time from 13 different customers, the data represent 13 weeks of demand from a single customer. Also, the container size can change each week, but the size decision has to be made each week prior to knowing what the demand for that week will be. Develop a procedure that can be used to determine each week's container size decision that tries to maximize profit. It can be assumed that any demand for a week that is not filled is lost; this is becuase very little lost demand carries over to the next week as additional demand due to the people receiving the vaccine having many alternate sources for the vaccine.

Display the data¶

Line plot is used since the data is a time series.

In [4]:
plot(d, legend=false, xlabel="Week", ylabel="Demand", xticks=1:length(d))
Out[4]:

Don't see any trend or seasonality that would need to be accounted for in any model of the data. Most importantly, the variability does not show a long-term pattern, and so will assume the data is stationary. Stationarity and lack of trend/seasonality imply that the data can be randomly re-arranged (or permuted) and it would look the same. Can verify this:

In [5]:
using Random
plot(d[randperm(length(d))], legend=false, xlabel="Week", ylabel="Demand", xticks=1:length(d))
Out[5]:
In [6]:
plot(d[randperm(length(d))], legend=false, xlabel="Week", ylabel="Demand", xticks=1:length(d))
Out[6]:

The two plots of a random permutation of the demands also look stationary and lack trend/seasonality.

Upper bound: Size equals demand (perfect estimate)¶

In order to be able to compare the effectiveness of any procedure, an upper bound on total profit can be determined assuming that the size selected each week exactly matched that weeks demand.

In [7]:
Π_UB = (p - c)*sum(d)
Out[7]:
11340
In [8]:
Π_UB = sum([fπ(di,di) for di in d])
Out[8]:
11340
Procedure 1: Previous week's demand¶

The first, and simplest, procedure would be to use the previous week's demand as the size for the current week:

In [9]:
sum([fπ(d[i-1],d[i]) for i in 2:length(d)])
Out[9]:
6996

The first procedure can be extended to use more than just the previous week's demand. A problem then is how should two or more previous week's demands be used to determine the size for the current week. Since the data is stationary and lacks trend/seasonality we can use the following permutation assumption:

In order to easily see the differences between different approaches to using prior demand, it is convenient to assume that each of the 13 weeks is, in turn, considered the current week, and the size estimate will be made using the other 12 weeks as the prior demand. (One can imagine all of the 13 demands rotated in sequence to the right so that each demand is in turn the last demand.) For simplicity, all 13 weeks can be considered prior demand. Given a particular procedure, its effectiveness can be determined by calculating the total profit using the prior demand. This is equivalent to adding up the profit for each current week using the size determined by the prior demand because the prior demand for the same in each case.

Procedures 2 and 3: Mean and median prior demand¶
In [10]:
using Statistics
fΠ(mean(d),d), fΠ(median(d),d)
mean(d)
Out[10]:
218.07692307692307
Procedure 4: Max total profit size for one-time demand¶
In [11]:
fΠ(qᵒ,d)
Out[11]:
9406.999995349586

Procedure 4 is recommended since the data is stationary and lacks trend/seasonality. If the data has a trend/seasonality, techniques exist that can remove the trend/seasonality; for non-stationary data, would use only most recent data in any estimate and would not be able to make the permutation assumption.

Minimize Loss instead of Maximizing Profit¶

Instead of considering profit when using prior demand, can equivalently consider loss:

$ \quad \mbox{Loss: } l(q) = \begin{cases} c\,(q - d), & \mbox{if } q > d \\ (p - c)\,(d - q), & \mbox{otherwise } \end{cases} $

In [12]:
L_LB = 0
fl(q,di) = (q > di ? c*(q - di) : (p - c)*(di - q))
fL(q,d) = sum([fl(q,di) for di in d])
plot([fL(qi,d) for qi = 0:500], legend=false, xlabel="Demand", ylabel="Total Loss")
qᵒ = optimize(q -> fL(q,d), 0, 500).minimizer
scatter!([qᵒ],[fL(qᵒ,d)])
Out[12]:
In [13]:
Π_UB - fL(qᵒ,d)
Out[13]:
9406.99999534959

Ex 3: No Win Situation¶

In [14]:
p = 1
c = 1
fl(q,di) = (q > di ? c*(q - di) : (p - c)*(di - q))
fL(q,d) = sum([fl(q,di) for di in d])
plot([fL(qi,d) for qi = 0:500], legend=false, xlabel="Demand", ylabel="Total Loss")
qᵒ = optimize(q -> fL(q,d), 0, 500).minimizer
display(scatter!([qᵒ],[fL(qᵒ,d)]))
qᵒ, fΠ(qᵒ,d)
Out[14]:
(32.93961234841663, 0.0)

Ex 4: Symmetric Loss¶

If $(p - c) = c $, then the loss is symmetric if $ q > d $ or $ q \le d $.

L1 loss: Absolute deviation¶

When the loss is constant with respect to its magnitude, then the loss is termed L1 loss and corresponds to the absolute value of the deviation of $q$ from $d$:

$ \quad \mbox{L1 loss: } l_1(q) = \bigl| q - d \bigr| $

In [15]:
p = 2
c = 1
fl(q,di) = (q > di ? c*(q - di) : (p - c)*(di - q))
fL(q,d) = sum([fl(q,di) for di in d])
plot([fL(qi,d) for qi = 0:500], legend=false, xlabel="Demand", ylabel="Total L1 Loss")
qᵒ = optimize(q -> fL(q,d), 0, 500).minimizer
display(scatter!([qᵒ],[fL(qᵒ,d)]))
qᵒ, fΠ(qᵒ,d)
Out[15]:
(160.9999992292811, 1780.9999992292812)

Mean vs median¶

In [16]:
mean(d), median(d)
Out[16]:
(218.07692307692307, 161.0)

L2 loss: Square error¶

When the loss is not constant with respect to its magnitude, then the most common loss is square error, or L2 loss:

$ \quad \mbox{L2 loss: } l_2(q) = (q - d)^2 $

In [17]:
fl2(q,di) = (q - di)^2
fL2(q,d) = sum([fl2(q,di) for di in d])
qᵒ = optimize(q -> fL2(q,d), 0, 500).minimizer
Out[17]:
218.0769230769231

MSE vs MAD¶

L2 loss is the only loss function that by minimizing (minimum square error, MSE) allows the mean of the data to be determined; most importantly, any change in data is reflected in a change to the mean and so the mean allows full information recovery. Minimizing L1 symmetric loss (minimum absolute deviation, MAD) correpsonds to the median of data and does not allow full information recovery, which in some cases is a good feature because it makes any estimate more robust with respect to outliers.

2. Non-numeric Arrays and Tuples¶

Arrays can have any data type as their elements. Unlike a regular matrix, an array can be used to store arrays of different lengths:

In [18]:
c = [[10, 20, 30], 40, [50, 60]]
Out[18]:
3-element Vector{Any}:
   [10, 20, 30]
 40
   [50, 60]

The individual top-level elements in the array are each an array that can be accessed:

In [19]:
c[1]
Out[19]:
3-element Vector{Int64}:
 10
 20
 30

To access an element in the second-level array:

In [20]:
c[1][1]
Out[20]:
10

To add an element to the end of a second-level array:

In [21]:
push!(c[1],35)
Out[21]:
4-element Vector{Int64}:
 10
 20
 30
 35

To add an element to the end of the top-level array:

In [22]:
push!(c,[1:2:10;])
Out[22]:
4-element Vector{Any}:
   [10, 20, 30, 35]
 40
   [50, 60]
   [1, 3, 5, 7, 9]

Arrays can be used to store text strings:

In [23]:
t = ["Miami","Detroit","Boston"]
Out[23]:
3-element Vector{String}:
 "Miami"
 "Detroit"
 "Boston"

Many functions can accept arrays of strings as input:

In [24]:
t = sort(t)
Out[24]:
3-element Vector{String}:
 "Boston"
 "Detroit"
 "Miami"
In [25]:
idxDetroit = findall("Detroit" .== t)
Out[25]:
1-element Vector{Int64}:
 2

If not sure of capitalization, can convert to lowercase before string matching:

In [26]:
isDetroit = "detroit" .== lowercase.(t)
Out[26]:
3-element BitVector:
 0
 1
 0
In [27]:
lowercase.(t)
Out[27]:
3-element Vector{String}:
 "boston"
 "detroit"
 "miami"

Tuples¶

A tuple is similar to an array, but differs in that, it is defined using ( ) instead of [ ] and, once defined, it cannot be changed and is immutable. A tuple is used to display multiple outputs:

In [28]:
a = 1; b = 2; c = 3;
a, b, c
Out[28]:
(1, 2, 3)
In [29]:
a,b,c = 1,2,3
Out[29]:
(1, 2, 3)
In [30]:
a
Out[30]:
1

A tuple can be used to store all of the input arguments for a function:

In [31]:
abc = (1, 2, 3)
Out[31]:
(1, 2, 3)
In [32]:
abc[1]
Out[32]:
1

Define a function of three inputs:

In [33]:
f(x,y,z) = x + y * z
f(a, b, c)
Out[33]:
7

The single-input tuple abc can be used instead to pass to "splat" the inputs a, b, c to the function by using ... following the tuple:

In [34]:
f(abc...)
Out[34]:
7

3. Dataframes¶

The Dataframe package can be used to work with structured tabular (i.e., row-column) data. To create a single-row table:

In [35]:
using DataFrames
df = DataFrame(Name = "Mike", Age = 44)
Out[35]:

1 rows × 2 columns

NameAge
StringInt64
1Mike44

To add a row to the table:

In [36]:
push!(df,("Bill",40))
Out[36]:

2 rows × 2 columns

NameAge
StringInt64
1Mike44
2Bill40

To create a two-row table:

In [37]:
df = DataFrame(Name = ["Mike","Bill"], Age = [44, 40])
Out[37]:

2 rows × 2 columns

NameAge
StringInt64
1Mike44
2Bill40

To access portions of a table:

In [38]:
name = df.Name
Out[38]:
2-element Vector{String}:
 "Mike"
 "Bill"
In [39]:
df.Age
Out[39]:
2-element Vector{Int64}:
 44
 40
In [40]:
df[2,:]
Out[40]:

DataFrameRow (2 columns)

NameAge
StringInt64
2Bill40
In [41]:
df[2,"Name"]
Out[41]:
"Bill"
In [42]:
df = DataFrame(x = [[1:5;]])
Out[42]:

1 rows × 1 columns

x
Array…
1[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
In [43]:
df.x
Out[43]:
1-element Vector{Vector{Int64}}:
 [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
In [44]:
df.x[1]
Out[44]:
5-element Vector{Int64}:
 1

 4
